[[File:Rio Grande RT Hill 1899b.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Rio Grande]], where Kelly's body was allegedly dumped.]]
The '''Lost Nigger Gold Mine''' is a legendary mine in the [[folklore of the United States]]. According to the legend, in 1887 four brothers in [[Dryden, Texas]]‚ÄîFrank, Jim, John, and Lee Reagan‚Äîhired an illiterate [[Seminole]] man named William Kelly to help with work on their ranch. Kelly was known as "Nigger Bill" (''nigger'' being a term for a multiracial person in the slang of the [[Big Bend (Texas)|Big Bend]] region){{sfn|Braddy|1945|p=360}} and has been identified as a cook{{sfn|"New Search"|1960|p=53}} and also as a horse wrangler; at the time of his employment by the Reagans, he was only 14.{{sfn|Porter|1954|p=19}} While working on the ranch, Kelly announced that he had discovered a gold mine, and was "greeted only with jeers". The next day he again tried to tell the Reagans about the mine, even going so far as to show them a lump of gold ore, but received a "cussing out" for his trouble.{{sfn|Porter|1954|p=13}}

After this rejection, Kelly went to [[San Antonio]], where he knew a white [[Metallurgical assay|assayer]], and asked him to analyze the ore. Stories then conflict: One account states that he returned to Dryden, where the Reagans received a letter addressed to him that confirmed the gold was immensely valuable, and then killed him and dumped his body in the [[Rio Grande]].{{sfn|Braddy|1945|p=360}} The other states that, shortly after returning, he "borrowed" a horse and fled. Whatever the case, the Reagans dedicated their lives to attempting to find the mine; one report from 1930 claims that the three Reagans alive at that point had still not given up on their search.{{sfn|Porter|1954|p=14}} As well as the Reagans, many other expeditions set out in search of the mine; the legend has it that, while some explorers did discover it, they always died before they could make a profit or pass on the information.{{sfn|Porter|1954|p=14}}

One of the more serious searches was instigated by [[William Broderick Cloete]], a British mine owner who believed in the story so completely that he offered Lock Campbell, a Texan man, expenses of $10,000 if he would undertake an expedition to find it.{{sfn|Dobie|1978|p=155}} On July 19, 1899, Campbell and four other men signed an agreement to search for it, and one of the men later claimed to have discovered it in the [[Ladron Peak|Ladrones Mountains]] in [[New Mexico]], but this was never verified. In 1909, an Oklahoman named Wattenberg traveled to [[Alpine, Texas]], with a map that he claimed showed the mine to be in Mexico itself; a pioneer named John Young went so far as to enter into partnership with Wattenberg and secure a mining permit from [[Porfirio D√≠az]], only to spend years fruitlessly trying to find it.{{sfn|Braddy|1945|p=360}} These failures have led to debates as to what happened to the mine. Young himself believed that it had been deliberately hidden by prospectors following Kelly;{{sfn|Braddy|1945|p=361}} another theory is that the gold was not actually gold ore, but instead pieces of refined gold left by the Spanish.{{sfn|Braddy|1945|p=362}} A third theory is that the gold was dropped by a group of Mexicans fleeing the ''[[rurales]]'', who were forced to abandon it because it was slowing them down. Another is that, as the gold mine was allegedly in a canyon, gravel could have washed down and hidden it from view.{{sfn|Dobie|1978|p=156}}

