[[File:Melin_Bompren,_Sain_Ffagan.jpg|250px|thumb|Melin Bompren in its present location at St Fagans]] '''Melin Bompren''' (''English:'' "Woodenbridge Mill") is a water-powered [[corn mill]], originally located at [[Cross Inn]], Cardiganshire, Wales, but now at the [[St Fagans National History Museum]], Cardiff.
The mill was built in 1853 to grind [[cereal|corn]] into [[flour]].<ref>[http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/en/stfagans/buildings/bompren/ Historical Buildings - St Fagans National History Museum: Bompren Corn Mill]. Accessed 1 October 2013</ref> It also has a [[kiln]] attached, which was used for drying [[oat]]s when the mill was in its original location.<ref>[http://www.welshmills.org.uk/bompren.m0s.html Welsh Mills Society: Melin Bompren at St Fagans]. Accessed 1 October 2013</ref>
The mill went out of use in 1957. In 1970 a decision was made to move it to St Fagans, where it opened to the public in 1977.
The name of the mill originates in the Welsh language as "Woodenbridge mill", "Bompren" is a development on "Bont Pren" which means "Wooden Bridge".
The mill is sometimes occupied by a skilled miller, who operates the grinding mill and explains its workings to visitors.<ref>[http://education.gtj.org.uk/en/item1/28945 Gathering the Jewels: The Melin Bompren Corn Mill, St Fagans] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20131001174045/http://education.gtj.org.uk/en/item1/28945 |date=2013-10-01 }}. Accessed 1 October 2013</ref>
